{"cursor":"16404","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox language |name=Ugaritic |states=ancient Ugarit |extinct=twelfth\ncentury BC |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=Semitic |fam3=Central Semitic\n|fam4=Northwest Semitic |iso2=uga|iso3=uga |notice=IPA}}\n\nThe 'Ugaritic language', a Northwest Semitic language, Though usually\nclassified as Northwest Semitic (Tropper, Josef \"Ugaritic grammar\", in\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=0Z2Jo01iq1YC&pg=PA91 Handbuch der\nOrientalistik], Wilfred G. E. Watson, editor (1999). BRILL, ISBN 90-04-10988-9,\nISBN 978-90-04-10988-9), Ugaritic is alternatively classified in a \"North\nSemitic\" group (LipiÅski, Edward (2001).\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=IiXVqyEkPKcC&pg=PA50 Semitic languages:\noutline of a comparative grammar]. Peeters Publishers, ISBN 90-429-0815-7, ISBN\n978-90-429-0815-4, 780 pages. Volume 80 of Orientalia Lovaniensia\nanalecta). discovered by French archaeologists in 1928, is known almost\nonly in the form of writings found in the ruined city of Ugarit (modern Ras\nShamra), Syria. Schniedewind, William M. and Hunt, Joel H. (2007).\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=L2T_4KVwpTQC&pg=PA20 A primer on Ugaritic:\nlanguage, culture, and literature] (p. 20). Cambridge University Press, ISBN 0-521-87933-\n7, ISBN 978-0-521-87933-0, 226 pages. Edward L. Greenstein,\n\"Texts from Ugarit Solve Biblical Puzzles\", [[Biblical Archaeology Review|BAR]]\n36:06, Nov/Dec 2010, pp. 48-53, 70. Found at [http://www.bib-\narch.org/bar/article.asp?PubID=BSBA&Volume=36&Issue=6&ArticleID=5 Biblical\nArchaeology Review website]. Accessed October 29, 2010. It has been used\nby scholars of the Old Testament to clarify Biblical Hebrew texts and has\nrevealed ways in which ancient Israelite culture finds parallels in the\nneighboring cultures.\n\nUgaritic has been called \"the greatest literary discovery from antiquity since\nthe deciphering of the Egyptian hieroglyphs and Mesopotamian cuneiform\". at\np. 9